रोता है रातों में
पाकिस्तां क्या वैसे ही
जैसे हिन्दोस्तां
ओ हुसना
means he is asking do you also feel the way I do... true love only existed in those days only ( no internet days )

snippet.textDisplay: Husna, the pseudo character, doesn't stand only for a lover's  letter, rather than the narrator intertwines the polytheistic harmony of previous Lahore with her. She or that very Husna, whose name literally means beautiful,  refers to the old time, the nostalgia that has been shattered  by borders. And the song is result of separation - not of two humans; rather of two new geographies which were one whole previously. And the chery on top of the lyrics, is the style of presentation and the pronunciation that perfectly captures the trauma!!
snippet.textOriginal: Husna, the pseudo character, doesn't stand only for a lover's  letter, rather than the narrator intertwines the polytheistic harmony of previous Lahore with her. snippet.textDisplay: I listen to this song again and again and I cry out in my silence. I miss him alot. I don't know if he ever gets to know this but this song is one such piece to live him. We used to listen to this in the canal of Lahore early morning. He left me and now it never existed for him. It does exist for me each night after a year and I do cry out and ask my Allah if he sees my pain. I don't share this agony. I just miss him. Kabhi kabhi usko yaad krne k liye ye song kaafi hai
